Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class HasLongSet<T extends HasLongRepresentation>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.HasLongSet<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Iterable<T>
Direct Known Subclasses:
IidSet
public abstract class HasLongSet<T extends HasLongRepresentation>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<T>
This is a special implementation of an RBSet (SORT OF) for the cases where the key class implements HasLongRepresentation. In those cases, we can key off of the long, and can therefore use specialized classes which are faster and more space-efficient (which can also result in speed increases due to fewer cache misses, presumably).

This is used in IidSet in particular, but can also be used for other cases of HasLongRepresentation (AssetId, Investable, AssetClass, etc.)

I originally wanted to make this look just like RBSet, so that the code can be agnostic about whether it's using a special implementation for the cases However, it's just not possible. The GNU Trove objects that we use for the raw underlying set do not really support a java.util.Set-like interface.

Therefore, any code that uses this will need to treat this specially (i.e. not like an RBSet).

See Also:
RBSet, HasLongMap
